The Pantanal fire, Brazil

Its a Data Science Workflow

With the extreme drought driven by the strong El Nio of 2023, forest fires broke records in the Pantanal. In the first 20 days of November, 2023, the biome has already had 3,957 fire outbreaks, around nine times higher than the average for the month in the last 25 years, which is 442 hot spots. The data are from the Queimadas Program, from the National Institute for Space Research (INPE). WWF

Observing vegetation health from space

We will look at the destruction and recovery of vegetation using NDVI (Normalized Difference Vegetation Index). How does it work? First, we need to learn about spectral reflectance signatures.

Every object reflects some wavelengths of light more or less than others. We can see this with our eyes, since, for example, plants reflect a lot of green in the summer, and then as that green diminishes in the fall they look more yellow or orange. The image below shows spectral signatures for water, soil, and vegetation.

Resources:

  • SEOS Project
  • Healthy leaves reflect a lot of NIR radiation compared to dead or stressed leaves
  • earthdatascience.org
  • USGS

Repeating tasks in Python

Now you should have a few dozen files! For each file, you need to:

  • Load the file in using the rioxarray library
  • Get the date from the file name
  • Add the date as a dimension coordinate
  • Give your data variable a name
  • Divide by the scale factor of 10000

Task

  • Look at the file names. How many characters from the end is the date?
  • Replace any required variable names with your chosen variable names
  • Change the scale_factor variable to be the correct scale factor for this NDVI dataset (HINT: NDVI should range between 0 and 1)
  • Using indices or regular
In[10]:
scale_factor = 10000
doy_start = -19  # indexes in the filename
doy_end = -12
In[11]:
ndvi_das = []
for ndvi_path in ndvi_paths:
    # Get date from file name
    doy = ndvi_path[doy_start:doy_end]
    date = pd.to_datetime(doy, format='%Y%j')
    print(doy, date)

    # Open dataset
    da = rxr.open_rasterio(ndvi_path, masked=True).squeeze()

    # Add date dimension and clean up metadata
    da = da.assign_coords({'date': date})
    da = da.expand_dims({'date': 1})
    da.name = 'NDVI'

    # Multiple by scale factor
    da = da / scale_factor

    # Prepare for concatenation
    ndvi_das.append(da)

Tasks

For both inside and outside the fire boundary:

  • Group the data by year
  • Take the mean. You always need to tell reducing methods in xarray what dimensions you want to reduce. When you want to summarize data across all dimensions, you can use the ... syntax, e.g..mean(...) as a shorthand.
  • Select the NDVI variable
  • Convert to a DataFrame using the to_dataframe() method
  • Join the two DataFrames for plotting using the .join() method. You will need to rename the columns using the lsuffix= and rsuffix= parameters
  • Plot annual Nov means for both inside and outside the Reservation on the same plot.
In[61]:
# Compute mean annual Nov NDVI
nov_ndvi_in_df = (
    ndvi_in_da
    .groupby(ndvi_in_da.date.dt.year)
    .mean(...)
    .NDVI.to_dataframe())

nov_ndvi_out_df = (
    ndvi_out_da
    .groupby(ndvi_out_da.date.dt.year)
    .mean(...)
    .NDVI.to_dataframe())

# Plot inside and outside Pantanal
nov_ndvi_df = (
    nov_ndvi_in_df[['NDVI']]
    .join(
        nov_ndvi_out_df[['NDVI']], 
        lsuffix=' Burned Area', rsuffix=' Unburned Area')
)

# + 20KB
nov_ndvi_df.hvplot(
    title='NDVI Nov Time Series for Pantanal boundary')
Out[61]:

According to this plot we can see that:

  • In 2002 and in 2023 the whole rectangular area was damaged by the fire.
  • From 2000 up to 2014 (except 2002) the burned area was concentrated in Pantanal polygon.
  • In 2020 the fire was concentrated within Pantanal polygon.

Showing the difference between outside and inside Pantanal

# Plot difference inside and outside Pantanal
nov_ndvi_df['difference'] = (
    nov_ndvi_df['NDVI Unburned Area']
    - nov_ndvi_df['NDVI Burned Area'])

# + 16KB
nov_ndvi_df.difference.hvplot(
    title='Difference between NDVI within and outside Pantanal'
)
Out[63]:

According to this plot we can see that:

  • In the years 2000, 2005, 2013 and 2020, the fire was concentrated in Pantanal's polygon
  • In 2017 there where, practically, no difference between inside and outside Pantanal vegetation.
